    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-04-17T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-04-17T16:00:00-05:00" n="167"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d167">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">741.60c/68: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-04-17T22:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 17, 1939—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 17—4:31 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>505. The Foreign Office informs me that the British Ambassador at Warsaw has been
                    advised by Beck<note n="64" xml:id="d167fn64">Józef Beck, Polish Minister for
                        Foreign Affairs.</note> that he was authorized to state Great Britain can
                    count on the assistance of Poland if she is involved in a war with Germany by
                    reason of an attack made on any of the <pb facs="0181" n="169" xml:id="pg_169"/>
                    smaller western European countries such as Belgium or Holland. At Beck’s request
                    this communication is not to be made public.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennedy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
